  "summary": "While Raoul is bound to a chair by Madame de Winter, Madame Iex attempts to reach the manifested child. Despite Raoul’s terrified commands to sit down for the medium's protection, Madame Iex insists the child is her own flesh and blood. As Madame Iex snatches the child into her arms, an anguished wail and a crunching sound erupt from behind a curtain. Madame Iex runs downstairs to unlock a door, while Raoul manages to break free from his ropes just as Iris arrives. Together, they pull back the curtain to discover a gruesome scene: Madame Iex is dead, and her body appears to have shrunk to half its original size. While Elise questions the cause of this phenomenon, Raoul is left in a state of distraught confusion.\n\nIn a different setting, the Dinsmoor family—consisting of the burly Mr. Dinsmoor, his wife, and their children Johnny and Margaret—is having a dinner of eggs, beef, bread, and cheese. Mr. Dinsmoor dismisses Margaret’s fears regarding ghosts, asserting that miracles do not occur. Their meal is interrupted by a sudden knock at the door.\n\nMortimer Cleveland, a researcher in psychosciences and parapsychology, has become stranded in the Wiltshire hills after a storm punctured his car tires. Following flickering lights, he seeks refuge at a small house. Upon knocking, he hears whispers from within before a fifteen-year-old boy opens the door. From the threshold, Cleveland observes the family, noting the robust father, the pale and frightened mother, and a surprised girl at the table.",
